<P>
<B>by Jonny</B>
<P>
Choosing a race:  Human is the only race that can be a monk so the choice is obvious.  The only real question is whether you want to start in Queynos or Freeport.  Personally I have a preference for Freeport since it's located closer to the center of Norrath and gives you easy access to the continent of Faydwer.   Queynos has its advantages as well though.  If you're playing on the pvp server and want to level quickly, you won't be impeded by all the racial warfare that goes on outside of Freeport.  But if you want to get involved in race warfare right away, Freeport is the place to be.  Agnostic monks begin in Queynos; their more superstitious brethren begin in Freeport.
<P>
Statistic Distribution: Agility and stamina are the two most important attributes for a monk in my experience.  I wouldn't recommend putting any points into strength since you don't seem to punch any harder.  Monks need to keep their weight at 14 pounds so added strength won't help you carry more loot either.  Agility affects how often you avoid hits and how often you dodge and this is essential to the monk's livelyhood so I'd recommend putting 15 points into this attribute.  The remaining 5 can either go into stamina or possibly even dexterity.  I've heard claims that higher dexterity means you block hits more often, but this is anecdotal and no real tests have been performed.  For this reason I'd recommend putting the remaining 5 into stamina to give you an extra hit point per level.  
<P>
Training:  You get 5 training points per level.  The first thing you need to do as a character is find your guild (read the city guide of Queynos or Freeport to get directions to your guild).  You begin with a note that you are supposed to give to your guild master.  When you get to your guild, give him the note and you'll receive a small amount of experience and a guild tunic.  Right click on your guild master again and you'll open the training window and a list of skills you can train in will be displayed.  You begin with 5 training opportunities and will get 5 more at each level.  The first thing you want to train is dodge.  You're supposed to begin with dodge but there's a bug which treats it as a newly acquired skill (any time you acquire a new skill, you have to train it once before it starts to raise).  At first level, dodge is the only skill that requires this.  Only put 1 point in to prime it and it will soon max out.  I'd recommend putting the last 4 into mend.  It's not an easy skill to raise since you can only use it once every 6 minutes so I always put at least 2 or 3 trains in it per level up until 19th.  Some people say you should train in punch and kick but these will rise quickly since you will be using them constantly.  Mend on the other hand can be painfully annoying to raise.  You'll learn more about mend down below.
<P>
Creating your Combat Menu:  You have 3 options for viewing the world of Norrath.  To see these three possibilities, hit F10 3 times.  Most people go for the middle view with the translucent panels though some of the hardcore gamers go for the pure view and rely entirely on hot keys.  I'd recommend the translucent panels since it gives you the best of both worlds.  In the lower left hand corner you'll see a menu with a number 1 above it.  This is one of six palettes with which to form your essential command buttons.  A monk needs 4 buttons on his main menu: melee attack, kick, range attack and mend.  To do this, click on the combat button to the right and a new menu will appear below it (you have to be in the miniature screen mode to do this).  Left click in the melee attack button and hold until the button appears to "come loose."  Now drag it over to the menu in the bottom left hand corner and place it over one of the slots and left click again and it should drop into the slot.  It may take a few tries since it has to be placed exactly on the slot.  Now do the same with range attack.  You'll notice that there are 4 combat ability buttons below melee and range attack.  Click on one and a list will appear to the left of possible abilities to put in this slot.  Select kick and kick will appear in that slot in the bottom right hand corner.  Now drag kick over to the left as you did with melee and range attack.  Click on a different combat skill and select mend.  Now drag mend over to the left.  You might want to put persona and sit in the other slots even though they have hot keys (i and 5).  To make a second menu, click on one of the arrows to the left or right of the 1 and a fresh palette will appear.  I always make a second menu with sit, camp, run/walk, invite and disband.  Now hit F10 an you'll see these buttons are still in the translucent boxes.  With these two palettes, you'll almost never have to leave the translucent box mode.
